Nothing beats a good design. But if really necessary, in addition to what commented you can trick GSON while deserializing with a type of your own. So for example creating class like:

	@SuppressWarnings(&quot;serial&quot;)
	public class CommonFeedList extends ArrayList&lt;CommonFeed&gt; {
		@Override
		public boolean add(CommonFeed commonFeed) {
			if(commonFeed.getDate() == 0) {
				return false;
			}
			return super.add(commonFeed);
		}
	} 

and with a little modification to your `Response` class:

	class Result {        
		@SerializedName(&quot;common_feed&quot;)
		CommonFeedList commonFeed;
        ...
	}

The con of course is that changing the list type also prevents to serialize nothing else than &quot;DD type&quot; of `CommonFeed`. In that case you need another type to serialize all types.

Anyway this kind of stuff should not be used carelessly. Always check the possibility to change the design first.

